{"title_page": "Vanraj Bhatia", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian music composer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image = <!-- only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people. Non-free and \"fair use\" images, e.g. promo photos, CD/DVD covers, posters, screen captures, etc., will be deleted - see [[WP:NONFREE]] --> |\n|imagesize = 150px |\n| name = '''Vanraj Bhatia'''\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1927|5|31}}\n| birth_place = [[Bombay]], [[British India]]\n| height = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| yearsactive = \n| birth_name = \n| othername = \n| website =\n}}\n'''Vanraj Bhatia''' (Hindi: \u0935\u0928\u0930\u093e\u091c \u092d\u093e\u091f\u093f\u092f\u093e {{IPAc-en|v|\u0259|n|'|r|\u0251\u02d0|j|_|b|h|\u0251\u02d0|t|i|a\u02d0}} {{respell|van|RAJ|_|BHA|tia}}; born May 31, 1927)<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0080299/ IMDb Profile]</ref> is an Indian composer best known for his work in [[Parallel cinema|Indian New Wave cinema]] and his work with filmmaker [[Shyam Benegal]]. He is also one of the leading composers of [[Classical music|Western classical music]] in India.\n\nBhatia is a recipient of the [[National Film Award for Best Music Direction]] for the television film\u00a0''[[Tamas (film)|Tamas]]''\u00a0(1988), the [[Sangeet Natak Akademi Award]] for Creative and Experimental Music (1989) and India\u2019s fourth-highest civilian honour, the [[Padma Shri]] (2012).\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life and education===\nBhatia learnt [[Hindustani classical music]] as a student at New Era School in Bombay and learnt [[Classical_music|Western classical piano]] under Dr. Manek Bhagat<ref>https://www.livemint.com/Leisure/pV1cS0blnWIHBuXwTMa2VL/Vanraj-Bhatia--Thank-you-for-the-music.html</ref>. After earning his M.A. (English Honours) from [[Elphinstone College]], [[University_of_Mumbai|University of Bombay]] in 1949, he studied composition at the [[Royal Academy of Music]], London, where he passed with a Gold Medal in 1954.\n\nThereafter he entered the [[Paris Conservatory]] where he studied with [[Nadia Boulanger]] and [[Howard Ferguson (composer)|Howard Ferguson]] between 1954 and 1959. During his studies abroad, he received various scholarships, including the Sir Michael Costa Scholarship (1951\u201354), a [[Rockefeller Fellowship]] (1954\u201358), and a French Government Scholarship (1957\u201358).\n\n===Career===\nIn 1960, he started his career as Reader in Musicology in charge of Western Music, at the Faculty of Music [[Delhi University]], where he stayed until 1965.\n\nIn 1959, he created his first advertising [[jingle]] for Shakti Silk Sarees. From then on, he continued working for the advertising industry. Bhatia has created over 7,000 scores for advertising jingles, corporate and business films.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nHis first film as a music composer was ''[[Ankur (film)|Ankur]]'' (1974), and he soon became a regular composer for [[Shyam Benegal]] and other art film makers of the time.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://serenademagazine.com/series/know-your-composer/vanraj-bhatia |title=Vanraj Bhatia |date=2017-03-22 |work=Serenade |access-date=2017-07-21 |language=en-GB}}</ref> His most noted works in this period are ''[[Manthan]]'' (1976), ''[[Bhumika (film)|Bhumika]]'' (1977), ''[[Junoon (1978 film)|Junoon]]'' (1978), ''[[36 Chowringhee Lane]]'' (1981), ''[[Trikal]]'' (1985) and ''[[Mandi (film)|Mandi]]'' (1983) and ''[[Jaane Bhi Do Yaaro]]'' (1983).\n\nIn the following decade, his work was heard constantly<ref>[http://www.india-today.com/mtoday/profiles/vanraj.html Vanraj Bhatia profile at indiatoday]</ref> on Indian television with the title scores for TV series like Khandaan, Yatra, Lifeline, [[Bharat Ek Khoj|Discovery of India]], ''[[Wagle Ki Duniya]]'', and the made-for-TV film [[Tamas (film)|Tamas]] (1987), for which he received the [[National Film Award for Best Music Direction]] in 1988.\n\nIn 2012, the first act of his opera ''[[Agni Varsha]]'' was premiered in Queens, New York.\n\n==List of compositions==\n\n===Works for solo piano===\n* ''Sonata'' (c. 1950s)\n* ''Toccata No. 1 in Raag Bahar'' (c. 1950s)\n* ''Introduction and Retrograde'' (1959)\n* ''Fantasia and Fugue in C'' (1999)\n* ''Rhapsody on \u201cAgni Varsha\u201d'' (2007)\n* ''Gujarati Nursery'' (2010)\n\n===Chamber music===\n{{colbegin}}\n* ''Trio'' for clarinet, cello and piano (c. 1950s)\n* ''Quintet'' for flute, harp, viola and two cellos (c. 1950s)\n* ''Divertimento'' for bassoon and piano (1951)\n* ''Sonata'' for violin and piano (1954)\n* ''Indian Nursery: Pieces'' for piano four hands (1956)\n* ''Sonatina'' for violin and piano (1956)\n* ''Divertimento Pastoral'' for flute, oboe, two clarinets and bassoon (1957)\n* ''Sangeet Raat: Night Music'' for solo flute (1964)\n* ''Cyclic Variations'' for cello and harpsichord (1965)\n* ''Kaleidoscope'' for prepared piano and string quartet (1965)\n* ''Kaleidoscope'' for violin, viola, cello and piano (2002)\n* ''Reverie'' for cello and piano (2014)\n* ''Spring: An Awakening'' for string quartet (2018)\n{{colend}}\n\n===Vocal music===\n{{colbegin}}\n* ''Dhoon'' for voice and piano (c. 1950s)\n* ''Kinguri-Vali'' for soprano, violin and piano (1960)\n* ''Vasansi Jeernani'' for triple chorus (c. 1970s)\n* ''Rudranaam'' for triple chorus (1973)\n* ''Jaisalmer'' for unaccompanied chorus (1977)\n* ''Six Seasons'' for unaccompanied chorus (1988)\n* ''Tantra: Meditations'' for voice and piano (1994)\n* ''Transcendence'' for double chorus (2002)\n* ''Rig Veda Hymns'' for double chorus (2003)\n* ''Six Seasons'' for soprano and piano (2009)\n{{colend}}\n\n===Music for large ensemble===\n* ''Concerto in One Movement'' for piano and strings (1955)\n* ''Gita Govinda'' for orchestra (1951)\n* ''Sinfonia Concertante'' for strings (2001)\n\n===Opera===\n* ''Agni Varsha'' (2017)\n\n===Feature film scores===\n{{colbegin}}\n* ''[[The Householder]]'' (1963) \u2013 background score only\n* ''[[Ankur (film)|Ankur]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[Nishant (film)|Nishant]]'' (1975)\n* ''Ek Dal Mithi'' (c. 1976, unreleased)\n* ''[[Manthan]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[Bhumika (film)|Bhumika]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[Kondura|Anugraham/Kondura]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[Junoon (1978 film)|Junoon]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[36 Chowringhee Lane]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[Kalyug (1981 film)|Kalyug]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[Sazaye Maut]] (1981)\n* ''Je Peed Parai Jaane Re'' (1982)\n* ''[[Jaane Bhi Do Yaaro]] (1983)\n* ''[[Mandi (film)|Mandi]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[Hip Hip Hurray (film)|Hip Hip Hurray]]'' (1984)\n* ''Mohan Joshi Haazir Ho!'' (1984)\n* ''[[Tarang (film)|Tarang]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[Aghaat]]'' (1985) \u2013 song only\n* ''[[Khamosh]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[Massey Sahib]]'' (1985) \u2013 uncredited\n* ''Surkhiyaan'' (1985)\n* ''[[Trikaal]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[Mohre]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Pestonjee]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Susman (film)|Susman]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Percy (1989 film)|Percy]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Ajooba]]'' (1991) \u2013 background score only\n* ''[[Antarnaad]]'' (1991)\n* ''Jazeere'' (1991)\n* ''[[Kasba (film)|Kasba]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Pita (film)|Pita]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Bekhudi]]'' (1992) \u2013 background score only\n* ''[[Beta (film)|Beta]]'' (1992) \u2013 background score only\n* ''[[Chamatkar]]'' (1992) \u2013 background score only\n* ''[[Ramayana: The Legend of Prince Rama]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Suraj Ka Satvan Ghoda]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Damini]]'' (1993) \u2013 background score only\n* ''[[Sardar (1993 film)|Sardar]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Drohkaal|Droh Kaal]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[Mammo]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[Bangarwadi]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Naseem (film)|Naseem]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Bandish (1996 film)|Bandish]]'' (1996) \u2013 background score only\n* ''[[Ghatak:_Lethal|Ghatak]]'' (1996) \u2013 background score only\n* ''Katha Doan Ganpatraonchi'' (1996) \u2013 background score only\n* ''[[Sardari Begum]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[The Making of the Mahatma]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Jaya Ganga]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Char Adhyay]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Himalay Putra]]'' (1997) \u2013 background score only\n* ''[[Pardes (film)|Pardes]]'' (1997) \u2013 background score only\n* ''[[China Gate (1998 film)|China Gate]]'' (1998) \u2013 background score only\n* ''[[Samar (1999 film)|Samar]]'' (1999)\n* ''Dhaad'' (2000, released 2018)\n* ''[[Hari-Bhari]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Chameli_(film)|Chameli]]'' (2003) \u2013 background score only\n* ''[[Escape from Taliban|Escape from Taliban]]'' (2003) \u2013 background score only\n* ''[[Rules: Pyaar Ka Superhit Formula]]'' (2003) \u2013 background score only\n* ''Kahan Se Aaye Badarwa: Forgotten Showers''/''Bhagya Na Jaane Koi'' (2005/2017) \u2013 background score only\n* ''[[Halla Bol]]'' (2008) \u2013 only one song\n{{colend}}\n\n===Television scores===\n{{colbegin}}\n* ''[[Khandaan (TV series)|Khandaan]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[Katha Sagar]]'' (1986) \u2013 selected episodes\n* ''[[Yatra (1986 TV series)|Yatra]]'' (1986)\n* ''[[Tamas (film)|Tamas]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Bharat Ek Khoj]]'' (1988)\n* ''Naqab'' (1988)\n* ''[[Wagle Ki Duniya]]'' (1988)\n* ''Lifeline'' (1991)\n* ''Baingan Raja'' (c. 1990s)\n* ''[[Bible Ki Kahaniya|Bible Ki Kahaniyan]]'' (1993)*\t\t\n* ''[[Banegi Apni Baat]]'' (1994)\n* ''Sankranti'' (1997)\n{{colend}}\n\n===Documentary scores (selected)===\n{{colbegin}}\n* ''A Certain Childhood'' (1962)\n* ''To Light a Candle'' (1964)\n* ''A City in History'' (1966)\n* ''From Lagoon to Sea'' (1966)\n* ''[[The House That Ananda Built]]'' (1967)\n* ''An Area of Darkness'' (c. 1968)\n* ''Indian Youth: An Exploration'' (1968)\n* ''Water'' (1968)\n* ''Creative Artists: Amrita Sher-Gil'' (1969)\n* ''The Women of India'' (1975)\n* ''A Small Family'' (1976)\n* ''Nirnaya'' (1979)\n* ''Bombay: A City at Stake'' (1981)\n* ''Shaping a Future'' (1983)\n* ''Tata Steel: Seventy-Five Years of the Indian Steel Industry'' (1983)\n* ''Nehru'' (1984) \u2013 certain sections scored by Alexei Kozlov\n* ''Molly\u2019s Wish'' (1985)\n* ''Chocolate Story'' (1986)\n* ''Nature Symphony'' (1990)\n* ''The Love We Give for Nothing'' (1992)\n* ''Prabhupada: A Lifetime in Preparation'' (1996)\n* ''Purva Uttara: Past Forward'' (1997)\n{{colend}}\n\n===Theatre music===\n{{colbegin}}\n* ''[[The Threepenny Opera|Teen Takke Ka Swang]]'' (1970), directed by [[Ebrahim Alkazi]] and [[Fritz Bennewitz]]\n* ''A Man\u2019s a Man'' (1971), directed by [[Amal Allana]]\n* ''[[The Caucasian Chalk Circle]]'' (1972), directed by [[Ebrahim Alkazi]] and [[Fritz Bennewitz]]\n* ''Nisheeth'' (1972), directed by [[Shanta Gandhi]]\n* ''[[Tughlaq (play)|Tughlaq]]'' (1972), directed by [[Ebrahim Alkazi]]\n* ''[[Andha Yug]]'' (1974), directed by [[Ebrahim Alkazi]]\n* ''Son-et-Lumiere: The Nehru Memorial Museum and Library'' (1976), directed by [[Ebrahim Alkazi]]\n* ''[[The Good Person of Szechwan|Aurat Bhali Ramkali]]'' (1984), directed by [[Amal Allana]]\n* ''[[Othello]]'' (1991), directed by [[Alyque Padamsee]]\n* ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac]]''<ref>https://theatricalia.com/play/g2/cyrano-de-bergerac/production/dm9</ref> (1995), directed by [[Jatinder Verma]]\n* ''My Bollywood Summer'' (2005), directed by Sabera Shaik\n{{colend}}\n\n===Albums===\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Preeti Sagar]] \u2013 ''\u201cSpring Is Coming\u201d/\u201dAll Night and Day\u201d'' (1976)\n* ''Hi! Ho!'' (1986)\n* ''Indian Meditation Music'' (1993)\n* ''The Elements: Earth'' (1995)\n* ''The Bhagavad Gita, Vols. 1 & 2'' (1996)\n* ''Anant: The Endless'' (2001), re-released as ''The Spirit of the Upanishads'' (2007)\n* Ritika Sahni \u2013 ''Ritika'' (2001)\n* ''Vaishnava Jana To'' (2005) \u2013 only one song\n* ''Tiranga Tera Aanchal'' (2005)\n{{colend}}\n\n==Awards & recognition==\n* Lili Boulanger Memorial Fund (1957)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.umb.edu/lili_boulanger/past_winners |title=Past Winners |date= |publisher=University of Massachusetts, Boston |accessdate=26 July 2013}}</ref>\n* Bengal Film Journalists Association Award for Music: ''Manthan'' (1976), ''Bhumika'' (1977)<ref>http://www.downmelodylane.com/vanraj.html</ref>\n* [[Sur Singar Samsad Award]] for Best Classical Score/Song (1986, 1987)<ref>http://www.downmelodylane.com/vanraj.html</ref>\n* [[National Film Award for Best Music Direction]] for ''[[Tamas (film)|Tamas]]'' (1988)\n* [[Sangeet Natak Akademi Award]] for Creative and Experimental Music (1989)\n* Maharashtra Rajya Puraskar (1990)\n* [[Padma Shri]] (2012)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0080299}}\n* [http://www.indiaclub.com/shop/AuthorSelect.asp?Author=Vanraj+Bhatia Private albums of Vanraj Bhatia]\n* [http://movies.nytimes.com/person/81786/Vanraj-Bhatia/filmography Vanraj Bhatia filmography at NY Times]\n* [https://serenademagazine.com/series/know-your-composer/vanraj-bhatia Vanraj Bhatia]\n* [https://thereel.scroll.in/830547/the-vanraj-bhatia-interview-my-music-was-unique-then-and-is-perhaps-unique-even-now The Vanraj Bhatia interview: \u2018My music was unique then and is perhaps unique even now\u2019]\n\n{{NationalFilmAwardBestMusicDirection}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhatia, Vanraj}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Elphinstone College alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Music]]\n[[Category:Indian male composers]]\n[[Category:Indian film score composers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Sangeet Natak Akademi Award]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in arts]]\n[[Category:Hindi film score composers]]\n[[Category:Best Music Direction National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Conservatoire de Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Rockefeller Fellows]]\n[[Category:Jingle composers]]\n[[Category:Pupils of Nadia Boulanger]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian musicians]]\n[[Category:Male film score composers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian music composer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image = <!-- only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people. Non-free and \"fair use\" images, e.g. promo photos, CD/DVD covers, posters, screen captures, etc., will be deleted - see [[WP:NONFREE]] --> |\n|imagesize = 150px |\n| name = '''Vanraj Bhatia'''\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1927|5|31}}\n| birth_place = [[Bombay]], [[British India]]\n| height = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| yearsactive = \n| birth_name = \n| othername = \n| website =\n}}\n'''Vanraj Bhatia''' (Hindi: \u0935\u0928\u0930\u093e\u091c \u092d\u093e\u091f\u093f\u092f\u093e {{IPAc-en|v|\u0259|n|'|r|\u0251\u02d0|j|_|b|h|\u0251\u02d0|t|i|a\u02d0}} {{respell|van|RAJ|_|BHA|tia}}; born May 31, 1927)<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0080299/ IMDb Profile]</ref> is an Indian composer best known for his work in [[Parallel cinema|Indian New Wave cinema]] and his work with filmmaker [[Shyam Benegal]]. He is also one of the leading composers of [[Classical music|Western classical music]] in India.\n\nBhatia is a recipient of the [[National Film Award for Best Music Direction]] for the television film\u00a0''[[Tamas (film)|Tamas]]''\u00a0(1988), the [[Sangeet Natak Akademi Award]] for Creative and Experimental Music (1989) and India\u2019s fourth-highest civilian honour, the [[Padma Shri]] (2012).\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life and education===\nBhatia learnt [[Hindustani classical music]] as a student at New Era School in Bombay and learnt [[Classical_music|Western classical piano]] under Dr. Manek Bhagat<ref>https://www.livemint.com/Leisure/pV1cS0blnWIHBuXwTMa2VL/Vanraj-Bhatia--Thank-you-for-the-music.html</ref>. After earning his M.A. (English Honours) from [[Elphinstone College]], [[University_of_Mumbai|University of Bombay]] in 1949, he studied composition at the [[Royal Academy of Music]], London, where he passed with a Gold Medal in 1954.\n\nThereafter he entered the [[Paris Conservatory]] where he studied with [[Nadia Boulanger]] and [[Howard Ferguson (composer)|Howard Ferguson]] between 1954 and 1959. During his studies abroad, he received various scholarships, including the Sir Michael Costa Scholarship (1951\u201354), a [[Rockefeller Fellowship]] (1954\u201358), and a French Government Scholarship (1957\u201358).\n\n===Career===\nIn 1960, he started his career as Reader in Musicology in charge of Western Music, at the Faculty of Music [[Delhi University]], where he stayed until 1965.\n\nIn 1959, he created his first advertising [[jingle]] for Shakti Silk Sarees. From then on, he continued working for the advertising industry. Bhatia has created over 7,000 scores for advertising jingles, corporate and business films.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nHis first film as a music composer was ''[[Ankur (film)|Ankur]]'' (1974), and he soon became a regular composer for [[Shyam Benegal]] and other art film makers of the time.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://serenademagazine.com/series/know-your-composer/vanraj-bhatia |title=Vanraj Bhatia |date=2017-03-22 |work=Serenade |access-date=2017-07-21 |language=en-GB}}</ref> His most noted works in this period are ''[[Manthan]]'' (1976), ''[[Bhumika (film)|Bhumika]]'' (1977), ''[[Junoon (1978 film)|Junoon]]'' (1978), ''[[36 Chowringhee Lane]]'' (1981), ''[[Trikal]]'' (1985) and ''[[Mandi (film)|Mandi]]'' (1983) and ''[[Jaane Bhi Do Yaaro]]'' (1983).\n\nIn the following decade, his work was heard constantly<ref>[http://www.india-today.com/mtoday/profiles/vanraj.html Vanraj Bhatia profile at indiatoday]</ref> on Indian television with the title scores for TV series like Khandaan, Yatra, Lifeline, [[Bharat Ek Khoj|Discovery of India]], ''[[Wagle Ki Duniya]]'', and the made-for-TV film [[Tamas (film)|Tamas]] (1987), for which he received the [[National Film Award for Best Music Direction]] in 1988.\n\nIn 2012, the first act of his opera ''[[Agni Varsha]]'' was premiered in Queens, New York.\n\n==List of compositions==\n\n===Works for solo piano===\n* ''Sonata'' (c. 1950s)\n* ''Toccata No. 1 in Raag Bahar'' (c. 1950s)\n* ''Introduction and Retrograde'' (1959)\n* ''Fantasia and Fugue in C'' (1999)\n* ''Rhapsody on \u201cAgni Varsha\u201d'' (2007)\n* ''Gujarati Nursery'' (2010)\n\n===Chamber music===\n{{colbegin}}\n* ''Trio'' for clarinet, cello and piano (c. 1950s)\n* ''Quintet'' for flute, harp, viola and two cellos (c. 1950s)\n* ''Divertimento'' for bassoon and piano (1951)\n* ''Sonata'' for violin and piano (1954)\n* ''Indian Nursery: Pieces'' for piano four hands (1956)\n* ''Sonatina'' for violin and piano (1956)\n* ''Divertimento Pastoral'' for flute, oboe, two clarinets and bassoon (1957)\n* ''Sangeet Raat: Night Music'' for solo flute (1964)\n* ''Cyclic Variations'' for cello and harpsichord (1965)\n* ''Kaleidoscope'' for prepared piano and string quartet (1965)\n* ''Kaleidoscope'' for violin, viola, cello and piano (2002)\n* ''Reverie'' for cello and piano (2014)\n* ''Spring: An Awakening'' for string quartet (2018)\n{{colend}}\n\n===Vocal music===\n{{colbegin}}\n* ''Dhoon'' for voice and piano (c. 1950s)\n* ''Kinguri-Vali'' for soprano, violin and piano (1960)\n* ''Vasansi Jeernani'' for triple chorus (c. 1970s)\n* ''Rudranaam'' for triple chorus (1973)\n* ''Jaisalmer'' for unaccompanied chorus (1977)\n* ''Six Seasons'' for unaccompanied chorus (1988)\n* ''Tantra: Meditations'' for voice and piano (1994)\n* ''Transcendence'' for double chorus (2002)\n* ''Rig Veda Hymns'' for double chorus (2003)\n* ''Six Seasons'' for soprano and piano (2009)\n{{colend}}\n\n===Music for large ensemble===\n* ''Concerto in One Movement'' for piano and strings (1955)\n* ''Gita Govinda'' for orchestra (1951)\n* ''Sinfonia Concertante'' for strings (2001)\n\n===Opera===\n* ''Agni Varsha'' (2017)\n\n===Feature film scores===\n{{colbegin}}\n* ''[[The Householder]]'' (1963) \u2013 background score only\n* ''[[Ankur (film)|Ankur]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[Nishant (film)|Nishant]]'' (1975)\n* ''Ek Dal Mithi'' (c. 1976, unreleased)\n* ''[[Manthan]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[Bhumika (film)|Bhumika]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[Kondura|Anugraham/Kondura]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[Junoon (1978 film)|Junoon]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[36 Chowringhee Lane]]