publisher = [[Nintendo]] | date = October 30, 2018 | accessdate = October 30, 2018 }}</ref>\n| 5.52\n| 20.31\n| 9.13\n| 49.97\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{n/a}}\n| 8.20\n| 40.82\n! 22.86\n! 111.10\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2018-12-31<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2019/190131e.pdf | title = Consolidated Financial Highlights - Q3 FY2019 | publisher = [[Nintendo]] | date = January 31, 2019 | accessdate = January 31, 2019 }}</ref>\n| 7.74\n| 30.33\n| 12.94\n| 73.85\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{n/a}}\n| 11.60\n| 59.42\n! 32.27\n! 163.61\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2019-03-31<ref name=\"fisc y18q4\">{{Cite web | url = https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2019/190425e.pdf | title = Consolidated Financial Highlights - Q4 FY2019 | publisher = [[Nintendo]] | date = April 25, 2019 | accessdate = April 25, 2019 }}</ref>\n|8.23\n|34.64\n|14.01\n|84.31\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{n/a}}\n|12.50\n|68.57\n!34.74\n!187.25\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2019-06-30<ref name=\"fisc y20q1\">{{Cite web | url = https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2019/190730e.pdf | title = Consolidated Financial Highlights - Q1 FY2020 | publisher = [[Nintendo]] | date = July 30, 2019 | accessdate = July 30, 2019 }}</ref>\n|8.76\n|39.05\n|14.83\n|94.47\n|9.60\n|62.46\n|3.69\n|14.15\n!36.87\n!210.13\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2019-09-30<ref name=\"fisc y20q2\">{{Cite web | url = https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2019/191031e.pdf | title = Consolidated Financial Highlights - Q2 FY2020 | publisher = [[Nintendo]] | date = October 31, 2019 | accessdate = October 31, 2019 }}</ref><br/>{{small|NS/NS Lite}}\n|10.00<br/>{{small|9.61/0.39}}\n|44.93\n|16.64<br/>{{small|15.84/0.80}}\n|110.22\n|10.86<br/>{{small|10.33/0.54}}\n|74.43\n|4.17<br/>{{small|3.94/0.22}}\n|16.43\n!41.67<br/>{{small|39.72/1.95}}\n!246.01\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2019-12-31<ref name=\"fisc y20q3\">{{Cite web | url = https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/pdf/2020/200130e.pdf | title = Consolidated Financial Highlights - Q3 FY2020 | publisher = [[Nintendo]] | date = January 30, 2020 | accessdate = January 30, 2020 }}</ref><br/>{{small|NS/NS Lite}}\n|12.42<br/>{{small|11.06/1.36}}\n|57.34\n|20.87<br/>{{small|18.78/2.09}}\n|138.63\n|13.88<br/>{{small|12.60/1.28}}\n|94.01\n|5.32<br/>{{small|4.86/0.46}}\n|20.68\n!52.48<br/>{{small|47.30/5.19}}\n!310.65\n|}\n\n{{As of|2019|12|31|df=US}}, Nintendo has shipped 52.48 million Switch units, with over 47.3 million original Switch units and 5.19 million Switch Lite units.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/finance/hard_soft/index.html| title = IR Information : Sales Data - Dedicated Video Game Sales Units}}</ref> With these numbers the Switch has surpassed lifetime sales of the [[Wii U]] (13.6 million units), [[GameCube]] (21.7 million units), [[Nintendo 64]] (32.9 million units) and [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]] (49.1 million units).<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/357393/The_Nintendo_Switch_has_surpassed_52_million_lifetime_sales.php | title = The Nintendo Switch has surpassed 52 million lifetime sales | first = Chris | last = Kerr | date = January 30, 2020 | accessdate = January 30, 2020 | work = [[Gamasutra]] }}</ref> The rate of sales of the Switch, based on the number of months to reach 50 million units, had outpaced both the PlayStation 4 and Xbox One, and was on par with the [[PlayStation 2]] and the [[Nintendo DS]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://venturebeat.com/2020/01/30/nintendo-switch-ps4/ | title = Nintendo Switch reaches 50 million consoles sold faster than PlayStation 4 | first = Jeff | last= Grubb | date = January 31, 2020 | accessdate = January 31, 2020 | work = [[Venture Beat]] }}</ref>\n\nOver 310 million software titles have been sold for the Switch {{As of|2019|12|31|df=US|lc=y}}.<ref name=\"fisc y20q2\"/> Top sellers for the platform, exceeding 10 million units sold worldwide:<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ir/en/finance/software/index.html | title = Top Selling Title Sales Units | date = December 31, 2019 | accessdate = January 30, 2020 | publisher = [[Nintendo]] }}</ref>\n* ''Mario Kart 8 Deluxe'' \u2013 22.96 million\n* ''Super Smash Bros. Ultimate'' \u2013 17.68 million\n* ''Super Mario Odyssey'' \u2013 16.59 million\n* ''The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild'' \u2013 16.34 million\n* ''Pok\u00e9mon Sword'' and ''Shield'' - 16.06 million\n* ''Pok\u00e9mon: Let's Go, Pikachu!'' and ''Let's Go, Eevee!'' \u2013 11.76 million\n\n=== Financial impact ===\nNintendo's business performance, which had been struggling for several years, soared upon the release of the Switch. By May 23, 2017, the success of the Switch's launch raised Nintendo's stock price to its highest levels in seven years, and an increase in price of over 100% from the previous year. However, the price still trailed Nintendo's peak price by about half, back in 2007 when it had just released the Wii.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/switch-helps-nintendos-stock-reach-its-highest-poi/1100-6450300/ | title = Switch Helps Nintendo's Stock Reach Its Highest Point Since Wii | first = Kevin | last = Knezevic | date = May 25, 2017 | accessdate = May 25, 2017 | website = [[GameSpot]] | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170921001839/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/switch-helps-nintendos-stock-reach-its-highest-poi/1100-6450300/ | archivedate = September 21, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Nintendo's stock was further boosted a few days later to meet its eight-year high following [[Capcom]]'s announcement of plans to release the popular ''[[Monster Hunter Generations|Monster Hunter XX]]'' for the Switch.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/switchs-monster-hunter-xx-reveal-boosts-nintendos-/1100-6450372/ | title = Switch's Monster Hunter XX Reveal Boosts Nintendo's Rising Stock To 8-Year High | first = Kevin | last = Knezevic | date = May 26, 2017 | accessdate = May 26, 2017 | website = [[GameSpot]] | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170921000706/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/switchs-monster-hunter-xx-reveal-boosts-nintendos-/1100-6450372/ | archivedate = September 21, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Nintendo announced a partnership with [[Tencent]], the leading publisher for mobile games in China, to bring their title ''[[Arena of Valor]]'', the international version of their mainland Chinese game ''[[Wangzhe Rongyao]]'', to the Switch following its December 2017 release in Western markets on mobile platforms. The game has an estimated 200 million players, most in China, and analysts anticipated that Nintendo will be releasing the Switch in China by 2019 as part of this deal. As a result, Nintendo's stock price rose overnight on the news by 7%, reaching a nine-year high.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.rollingstone.com/glixel/news/nintendo-eyes-china-with-tencent-partnership-wsj-w504209 | title = Nintendo's Tencent Partnership Could Open Door to Switch In China: WSJ | first = Blake | last = Hester | date = September 19, 2017 | accessdate = September 20, 2017 | website = [[Glixel]] | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170919214531/http://www.rollingstone.com/glixel/news/nintendo-eyes-china-with-tencent-partnership-wsj-w504209 | archivedate = September 19, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/nintendo-deal-with-tencent-paves-way-for-china-push-1505825294 | title = Nintendo Surges on Prospect of Greater Access to China | first1 = Takashi | last1 = Mochizuki | first2 = Alyssa | last2 = Abkowitz | date = September 19, 2017 | accessdate = September 20, 2017 | website = [[The Wall Street Journal]] | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170919235720/https://www.wsj.com/articles/nintendo-deal-with-tencent-paves-way-for-china-push-1505825294 | archivedate = September 19, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.theverge.com/2017/12/18/16469736/tencent-arena-of-valor-honor-of-kings-north-america-launch | title = Tencent is bringing China's biggest game to the rest of the world | first = Andrew | last = Webster | date = December 18, 2017 | accessdate = December 18, 2017 | website = [[The Verge]] | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171219081138/https://www.theverge.com/2017/12/18/16469736/tencent-arena-of-valor-honor-of-kings-north-america-launch | archivedate = December 19, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Nintendo's stock reached its ten-year high shortly after the October 2017 expansion of Switch production to 2 million units per month and speculation that Nintendo would likely start selling the unit in China sooner than anticipated.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-10-09-switch-production-upped-to-two-million-per-month | title = Nintendo shares hit-ten year high | first = Haydn | last = Taylor | date = October 9, 2017 | accessdate = October 9, 2017 | website = [[GamesIndustry.biz]] | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171029113552/http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-10-09-switch-production-upped-to-two-million-per-month | archivedate = October 29, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nNintendo's quarterly reports, for the period ending September 30, 2017, showed a profit of $209 million, the first profitable quarter in several years, due to both success of the Switch and its mobile gaming strategy.<ref name=\"nytimes dec 2017\">{{Cite web | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/29/technology/nintendo-switch.html| title = Nintendo's Switch Brings Some Magic Back | first = Simon | last = Parkin | date = December 29, 2017 | accessdate = January 1, 2018 | website = [[The New York Times]] }}</ref> For similar reasons, its following quarter, ending December 31, 2017, was Nintendo's most profitable quarter since 2009, with year-to-year revenues increased by 177%.<ref name=\"bbc q3 2017\">{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-42885803 | title = Nintendo Switch overtakes the Wii U | date = January 31, 2018 | accessdate = January 31, 2018 | website = [[BBC News]] }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/31/nintendo-earnings-q3-2017.html | title = Nintendo ups its Switch sales expectations to 15 million units after profits rise 261% | first = Arjun | last = Kharpal | date = January 31, 2018 | accessdate = January 31, 2018 | website = [[CNBC]] }}</ref>\n\nNintendo's quarterly profit jumped by 44% in the first fiscal quarter of 2018 and their net profit totalled $274.9 million during April\u2013June 2018 due to new titles being released for the Switch such as ''Donkey Kong Country: Tropical Freeze''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://business.financialpost.com/pmn/business-pmn/nintendo-reports-big-jump-in-2nd-quarter-earnings|title=Nintendo reports jump in earnings thanks to Switch|date=July 31, 2018|work=Financial Post|access-date=October 12, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Sales of the Switch and its games helped increase Nintendo's operating profit by 30% during July\u2013September 2018 and helped Nintendo reach its highest quarterly result in 8 years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/technology/nintendo-second-quarter-profit-hits-eight-year-high--powered-by-switch-sales-10879146|title=Nintendo second-quarter profit hits eight-year high, powered by Switch sales|work=Channel NewsAsia|access-date=November 14, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nNintendo's quarterly profit jumped by 25% in the third fiscal quarter of 2018 due to the popularity of games on the Switch and their October\u2013December profit totalled $956 million, while quarterly sales totalled $5.6 billion, which were up by 26%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://business.financialpost.com/pmn/business-pmn/nintendos-quarterly-profit-rises-on-hit-switch-games|title=Nintendo's quarterly profit rises on hit Switch games {{!}} Financial Post|last=Kageyama|first=Yuri|date=January 31, 2019|website=Financial Post|language=en-CA|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=February 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nNintendo's yearly profit jumped by 39% during the April 2018-March 2019 fiscal year and annual sales rose 14% to $10.7 billion due to \"healthy\" software sales for the Switch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Business/wireStory/nintendo-profit-jumps-39-switch-software-sales-62619942|title=Nintendo profit jumps 39% on Switch software sales|last=Kageyama|first=Yuri|date=April 25, 2019|website=ABC News|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=April 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Legal issues ==\nIn August 2017, Los Angeles-based tablet peripheral manufacturer [[Gamevice|Gamevice, Inc.]] filed a lawsuit against Nintendo in the [[United States District Court for the Central District of California]], alleging that the design of the Switch conflicts with its patent on the design for the [[Wikipad]], an [[Android (operating system)|Android]]-based gaming device that also features a tablet with a detachable controller. The lawsuit sought damages on existing Switch sales and banning further sales of the console.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.engadget.com/2017/08/11/nintendo-faces-lawsuit-over-switch-controllers/?sr_source=Twitter | title = Nintendo faces lawsuit over the Switch's detachable controllers | first = Jon | last = Fingas | date = August 11, 2017 | accessdate = August 11, 2017 | website = [[Engadget]] | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170811142824/https://www.engadget.com/2017/08/11/nintendo-faces-lawsuit-over-switch-controllers/?sr_source=Twitter | archivedate = August 11, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> The lawsuit was voluntarily dismissed by Gamevice in October 2017.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://insight.rpxcorp.com/lit/cacdce-686108-gamevice-v-nintendo | title = Gamevice, Inc. v. Nintendo Co., Ltd. et al | publisher = [[RPX Corporation]] | accessdate = January 25, 2018 | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180614195357/https://insight.rpxcorp.com/lit/cacdce-686108-gamevice-v-nintendo | archivedate = June 14, 2018 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHowever, in March 2018, Gamevice initiated a second patent infringement lawsuit on Nintendo related to a different set of patents. Gamevice also sought action through the [[United States International Trade Commission]] related to patent infringement under Section 337 of the [[Tariff Act of 1930]], and was seeking to block imports of the Switch into the United States.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.engadget.com/2018/05/01/nintendo-switch-wikipad-gamevice-import-investigation-patent/ | title = Nintendo faces Switch patent infringement investigation in the US | first = Jessica | last = Conduit | date = May 1, 2018 | accessdate = May 1, 2018 | website = [[Engadget]] }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2018/5/6/17324594/nintendo-switch-sued-patent-infringement-gamevice | title = Nintendo sued by peripheral maker alleging Switch design infringes patents | first = Owen | last = Good | date = May 6, 2018 | accessdate = May 6, 2018 | website = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usitc.gov/press_room/news_release/2018/er0501ll939.htm|title=USITC Institutes Section 337 Investigation of Certain Portable Gaming Console Systems with Attachable Handheld Controllers and Components Thereof {{!}} USITC|website=www.usitc.gov|language=en|access-date=September 1, 2018}}</ref> The lawsuit would be terminated on October 10, 2019, with no such violations being found.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2019/10/10/2019-22172/certain-portable-gaming-console-systems-with-attachable-handheld-controllers-and-components-thereof|title=Certain Portable Gaming Console Systems With Attachable Handheld Controllers and Components Thereof; Notice of a Commission Determination Finding No Violation of Section 337; Termination of the Investigation|last=|first=|date=|website=US Federal Register|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref> By March 2020, the [[United States Patent and Trademark Office]] had reviewed Gamevice's patents and deemed all of its claims to be unpatentable, a ruling in favor of Nintendo. Gamevice stated they would be challenging the Office's decision.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2020-03-12-nintendo-wins-patent-dispute-against-gamevice | title = Nintendo wins patent dispute against Gamevice | first = James | last = Batchelor | date = March 12, 2020 | accessdate = March 12, 2020 | work = [[GamesIndustry.biz]] }}</ref>\n\nA [[class action lawsuit]] was filed in the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Washington]] in July 2019 concerning a joystick defect in the console's Joy-Con controllers, commonly referred to as \"drift\". The suit alleges that Nintendo is aware of a defect that causes the controllers to register movements without the joysticks being touched, but does not \"disclose the defect and routinely refuses to repair the joysticks without charge\".<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.videogameschronicle.com/news/nintendo-faces-lawsuit-over-drifting-joy-con-issue/ | title = Nintendo faces lawsuit over 'drifting' Switch Joy-Cons | first = Andy | last = Robinson | date =  July 20, 2019 | accessdate = July 20, 2019 | work = [[Video Games Chronicle]] }}</ref> Three days after the filing, an internal Nintendo company memo was leaked by ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]''; the memo instructed Nintendo's customer service employees in North America to begin offering repairs for drifting Joy-Con controllers free of charge regardless of warranty status.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/8xzzva/internal-nintendo-memo-instructs-customer-service-to-fix-joy-con-drift-for-free | title = Internal Nintendo Memo Instructs Customer Service to Fix 'Joy-Con Drift' for Free | first = Patrick | last = Klepek | date =  July 23, 2019 | accessdate = August 9, 2019 | work = [[Vice Games]] }}</ref> The lawsuit, however, continued, and following the release of the Nintendo Switch Lite where some on social media reported the Joy-Con drift problem after 20 hours of play, additional complaints related to the Lite were added to the lawsuit.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/nintendo-switch/2019/9/28/20888540/nintendo-switch-joy-con-drift-lawsuit-switch-lite-repairs | title = Joy-Con drift lawsuit adds Switch Lite to class-action complaint | first = Owen S. | last = Good | date = September 28, 2019 | accessdate = September 28, 2019 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref> While the court refused to grant Nintendo a dismissal of the case, it did agree to send the case into arbitration as a first step as outlined in the [[EULA]] for the Switch in a ruling made in March 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2020-03-11-joy-con-drift-lawsuit-denied-dismissal-but-referred-to-arbitration | title = Joy-Con drift lawsuit denied dismissal, but referred to arbitration | first = Rebekah | last = Valentine | date = March 11, 2020 | accessdate = March 12, 2020 | work = [[GamesIndustry.biz]] }}</ref>\n\nNintendo successfully obtained an injunction in December 2019 against a distributor of a hack made by Team-Xecuter that enabled Switch users to obtain and run copyright-violating copies of Switch games on the console.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2020-01-02-nintendo-wins-injunction-against-creator-of-switch-mod-that-allowed-large-scale-piracy | title = Nintendo wins injunction against creator of Switch mod that enabled piracy | first = Rebekah | last =Valentine | date =January 2, 2020 | accessdate = January 2, 2020 | work = [[GamesIndustry.biz]] }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Yuzu (emulator)|yuzu]], a Nintendo Switch emulator\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"eurogamer-sd-2019\">{{cite web |last1=Judd |first1=Will |title=The best Micro SD cards for Nintendo Switch 2019 |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/digitalfoundry-2019-05-09-the-best-micro-sd-cards-for-nintendo-switch-7000 |website=Eurogamer |accessdate= June 7, 2019 |date=June 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Nintendo Switch}}\n{{Nintendo hardware}}\n{{Eighth generation game consoles}}\n{{Home video game consoles}}\n{{Handheld game consoles}}\n{{Portal bar|Video games|Electronics}}\n\n[[Category:2017 in video games]]\n[[Category:2010s toys]]\n[[Category:2020s toys]]\n[[Category:ARM-based video game consoles]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2017]]\n[[Category:Eighth-generation video game consoles]]\n[[Category:Handheld game consoles]]\n[[Category:Home video game consoles]]\n[[Category:Nintendo]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch| ]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 2017]]\n[[Category:Regionless game consoles]]\n", "name_user": "Wongjessica", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDevelopment", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nintendo_Switch"}
{"title_page": "Home mortgage interest deduction", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Taxation}}\nA '''home mortgage interest deduction''' allows taxpayers who [[Owner-occupier|own their homes]] to reduce their [[taxable income]] <ref>http://www.articlesxpert.com/article/1260369/the-multiple-benefits-of-home-loan-tax-exemption/</ref> by the amount of [[interest]] paid on the [[loan]] which is secured by their principal residence (or, sometimes, a [[Vacation property|second home]]).  Most [[Developed country|developed countries]] do not allow a deduction for interest on personal loans, so countries that allow a home mortgage interest deduction have created an exception to those rules. The [[Netherlands]], [[Switzerland]], and the [[United States]] each allow the deduction. In [[Belgium]], [[Denmark]], and [[Ireland]], only a minor part of mortgage interest is deductible.\n\n== Status in countries ==\n\n=== Canada ===\nCanadian federal income tax does not allow a deduction from taxable income for interest on loans secured by the taxpayer's personal residence, but homes used in businesses as a landlord who owns a rental residential property can deduct interest as any other reasonable business expense. The difference being the deduction is allowed only when the property is not used for the taxpayer's personal use but is used as in any other type of business.<ref>https://turbotax.intuit.ca/tax-resources/tax-deductions/is-interest-deductible.jsp</ref> However, there may be additional exclusions for [[passive activity]] losses.\n\nAn indirect method, known as the Smith Manoeuvre, for making interest on mortgage for personal residence tax deductible in Canada is through an asset swap, whereby the homebuyer sells his existing investments, purchases a house in full or in part by the sale, gets a mortgage on the house, and finally, buys back his investments with the money from the mortgage.<ref>https://www.theglobeandmail.com/real-estate/mortgages-and-rates/the-smith-maneuver-a-canadian-mortgage-tax-deductible-plan/article12059456/</ref> The Supreme Court of Canada has ruled in 2001 in the Singleton v. Canada case<ref name=Singleton>{{Cite web |url=http://csc.lexum.umontreal.ca/en/2001/2001scc61/2001scc61.html |title=Supreme Court of Canada: Singleton v. Canada, 2001 2 S.C.R. 1046, 2001 SCC 61 |access-date=29 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100518203119/http://csc.lexum.umontreal.ca/en/2001/2001scc61/2001scc61.html |archive-date=18 May 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> that transactions in the asset swap are to be regarded as distinct, thus rendering the interest on home mortgage acquired as part of the asset swap tax deductible.\n\nThe home ownership rate in Canada was about the same as in the United States in 2008<ref>[http://www.newsweek.com/id/183670 Worthwhile Canadian Initiative]</ref> despite the difference in tax policy.\n\n=== Denmark ===\nIn Denmark part of the interest is deductible. In 1987 it was 73%. In 1993 it was 50% and in 1998 it was 46%. From 1998 to 2001 it was reduced to 32%. It is the plan that in 2019 it will be 25,5%.\n\n=== France ===\nFrance does not allow a home mortgage interest deduction. In 2007, newly elected President [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] proposed creating the deduction as part of his legislative plan for sparking the French economy.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=a9OlqDLbD9sU&refer=home | work=Bloomberg | title=Sarkozy Defeats Royal in French Presidential Runoff (Update5) | date=6 May 2007}}</ref> In August 2007, the [[Constitutional Council of France|Constitutional Council]], the highest court in France, struck down the mortgage interest deduction as unconstitutionally creating a tax advantage that goes far beyond its stated goal of encouraging non-homeowners to buy homes. The Court noted that the deduction would apply to people who already own homes.<ref>http://www.conseil-constitutionnel.fr/decision/2007/2007555/2007555dc.htm (French)</ref>\n\n=== India ===\nHome loan interest portion is deductible (under section 24(b)) up to 150 000 rupees in a tax year for acquiring or constructing a property. The deduction is available only when the construction is complete or you have possession of the property. Interest of pre-construction period is deductible in five equal installments. The first installment is deductible in the year in which construction of property is completed or property acquired. The principal is deductible under section 80C, which has a limit of 150 000 rupees.<ref>''[https://www.easyfinance.com/community/the-multiple-benefits-of-home-loan-tax-exemption/]'', Benefits of Home Loan Tax Exemption</ref><ref>http://mytaxes.in/index.php?topic=9.0 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101127140317/http://mytaxes.in/index.php?topic=9.0 |date=27 November 2010 }} Home Loan Deduction</ref>\n\n=== Netherlands ===\nIn the Netherlands, a part of the interest payments can be deducted for a maximum period of 30 years. The deduction percentage is based on a person's income.<ref>http://www.belastingdienst.nl/variabel/buitenland/en/private_taxpayers/private_taxpayers-12.html  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090401050427/http://www.belastingdienst.nl/variabel/buitenland/en/private_taxpayers/private_taxpayers-12.html |date=1 April 2009 }}</ref> However, before deduction the taxable income is increased by a percentage of the property value (so-called \"notional rental value\"<ref>http://www.belastingdienst.nl/variabel/buitenland/en/private_taxpayers/private_taxpayers-10.html , {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090417022804/http://www.belastingdienst.nl/variabel/buitenland/en/private_taxpayers/private_taxpayers-10.html |date=17 April 2009 }}</ref>) with the reasoning that the property has a potential income-generating purpose.\n\nStill in place currently, the mortgage interest tax deduction is subject to fierce debate, and a political issue during most recent elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nuzakelijk.nl/algemeen/2259623/verkiezingen-2010-hypotheekrenteaftrek-en-huur.html|title=Verkiezingen 2010: hypotheekrenteaftrek en huur|date=1 June 2010|publisher=nuzakelijk.nl|language=Dutch|accessdate=23 February 2012}}</ref> Although largely an emotional point of discussion with the Dutch electorate, and described by many as \"political suicide\", most Dutch people believe that the mortgage interest tax deduction will eventually be reformed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vorige.nrc.nl/krant/article1739149.ece/Taboe_voor_politici,_niet_voor_de_kiezers_|title=Taboe voor politici, niet voor de kiezers|date=11 April 2006|publisher=NRC Handelsblad|language=Dutch|accessdate=23 February 2012}}</ref> Many reasons for abolishment have been identified, often fuelled by a political ideology (e.g. creating house price inflation, limiting government earnings in times of economic downturn, mortgage interest tax deduction is increasing already high tax levels in the Netherlands, benefiting high income individuals more disproportionally).<ref>[[:nl:Hypotheekrenteaftrek]]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nos.nl/artikel/65097-hypotheekrente-weer-ter-discussie.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120929100106/http://nos.nl/artikel/65097-hypotheekrente-weer-ter-discussie.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-09-29 |title=Hypotheekrente weer ter discussie |date=2007-10-17 |publisher=NOS Nieuws |language=Dutch |accessdate=23 February 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bouwendnederland.nl/SiteCollectionDocuments/Argumenten%20voor%20-%20tegen%20beperking%20hypotheekrenteafttrek.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724145621/http://www.bouwendnederland.nl/SiteCollectionDocuments/Argumenten%20voor%20-%20tegen%20beperking%20hypotheekrenteafttrek.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 July 2011 |title=Argumenten voor - tegen beperking hypotheekrenteaftrek |publisher=BouwendNederland |language=Dutch |accessdate=23 February 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hypotheker.nl/Hypotheken/Hypotheekrenteaftrek/Veelgestelde+vragen/|title=Hypotheekrenteaftrek: Veelgestelde vragen|publisher=De hypotheker|language=Dutch|accessdate=23 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nAs it stands now, Dutch politicians and other organisations research possible strategies to end interest payments tax deduction and are fuelling public debate to prepare the Dutch public for eventual abolishment.<ref name=\"tns-nipo.com\">http://www.tns-nipo.com/pages/nieuws-pers-vnipo.asp?file=persvannipo\\pol_woningmarkt-08062010.htm {{Failed verification|date=February 2012}}</ref> Only 18% of the Dutch public support eliminating the mortgage interest deduction entirely.<ref name=\"tns-nipo.com\"/>\n\n=== Norway ===\nNorway considers ''any'' interest paid, whether it is for a home mortgage or other debt, as a deductible expense.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://snl.no/rentefradrag|title=rentefradrag|publisher=Store norske leksikon|language=Norwegian|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> The result is a reduction of the tax bill of 25% of all interest paid.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nettavisen.no/na24/smartepenger/rentefradraget-blir-mindre-verdt/3423145132.html|title=Rentefradraget blir mindre verdt|publisher=Nettavisen|language=Norwegian|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref> The fact that the government in effect subsidises 25% of the interest bill has made home ownership highly beneficial in Norway, and critics argue that the deduction has increased the cost of real estate. The [[Center Party (Norway)|Center Party]] has proposed reducing the deduction.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aftenbladet.no/nyheter/politikk/Sp-vil-kutte-rentefradrag-pa-private-boliglan-3153597.html#.UajYFkBJSZg|title=Sp vil kutte rentefradrag p\u00e5 private boligl\u00e5n|last=Natland|first=Jarle|date=7 April 2013|publisher=Aftenbladet|language=Norwegian|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Sweden ===\nA tax credit of 30% of interest up until 100,000 SEK, and 21% over that amount.<ref>https://www.skatteverket.se/privat/skatter/arbeteinkomst/avdragslexikon/r.4.5fc8c94513259a4ba1d800042806.html</ref> The amount was about 10,000 SEK per taxpaying person with debts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.svd.se/naringsliv/pengar/bostad/slopat-ranteavdrag-hot-for-familjer_3963920.svd|title=Slopat r\u00e4nteavdrag hot f\u00f6r familjer|date=29 September 2014|publisher=Svenska dagbladet|language=Swedish|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== United Kingdom ===\n\nThe United Kingdom introduced a scheme called [[Mortgage interest relief at source|MIRAS]] in 1983 to allow mortgage interest to be tax deductible. It was abolished in 2000.\n\n=== United States ===\n\nPrior to the [[Tax Reform Act of 1986]] (TRA86), the interest on all personal loans (including credit card debt) was deductible. TRA86 eliminated that broad deduction, but left the narrower home mortgage interest deduction.<ref name=Lowenstein2006 /><ref name=Duke_Law>{{ cite web | url=https://scholarship.law.duke.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1561&context=lcp | title=THE ACCIDENTAL DEDUCTION: A HISTORY AND CRITIQUE OF THE TAX SUBSIDY FOR MORTGAGE INTEREST | last=VENTRY | first=DENNIS | publisher=Duke University Law | date=2009 | accessdate=2018-01-19 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120126190952/https://scholarship.law.duke.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1561&context=lcp | archive-date=2012-01-26 | url-status=live | pages=236 | quote=<blockquote>Whatever the original motivation for the consumer interest deduction, one thing is clear: Congress did not see it as a way of promoting homeownership. ... Part II of this article examines the origins of the deduction for personal interest alongside the birth of the modern federal income tax and concludes that the deduction had nothing to do with encouraging or rewarding homeownership.</blockquote> }}</ref> While some Americans may believe that Congress created the home mortgage interest deduction as a way to encourage home ownership,<ref name=NYT_MID2>{{ cite web | url=https://economix.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/08/06/the-sacrosanct-mortgage-interest-deduction/ | title=The Sacrosanct Mortgage Interest Deduction | last=Bartlett | first=Bruce | publisher=The New York Times Company | date=2013-08-06 | accessdate=2018-01-19 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020203627/https://economix.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/08/06/the-sacrosanct-mortgage-interest-deduction/ | archive-date=2017-10-20 | url-status=live | quote=Contrary to popular belief, the mortgage interest deduction wasn\u2019t adopted to encourage home ownership. }}</ref><ref name=Tax_Policy_1>{{ cite web | url=http://www.taxpolicycenter.org/sites/default/files/briefing-book/4.8.2-do_existing_tax_incentives_increase_homeownership.pdf | title=Do existing tax incentives increase homeownership? | publisher=Taxpolicycenter.org | accessdate=2018-01-19 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119214832/http://www.taxpolicycenter.org/sites/default/files/briefing-book/4.8.2-do_existing_tax_incentives_increase_homeownership.pdf | archive-date=2018-01-19 | url-status=live | quote=Contrary to popular belief, the mortgage interest deduction was not added to the tax code to encourage home ownership. The deduction existed at the birth of the income tax in 1913\u2014a tax explicitly designed to hit only the richest individuals, a group for whom homeownership rates were not a social concern. }}</ref> historians point out that this was never the case, as explained in a New York Times article that notes that, in 1913, when interest deductions started, Congress \"certainly wasn't thinking of the interest deduction as a stepping-stone to middle-class home ownership, because the tax excluded the first $3,000 (or for married couples, $4,000) of income; less than 1 percent of the population earned more than that;\" moreover, during that era, most people who purchased homes paid upfront rather than taking out a mortgage. Rather, the reason for the deduction was that in a nation of small proprietors, it was more difficult to separate business and personal expenses, and so it was simpler to just allow deduction of all interest.<ref name=Lowenstein2006/><ref name=Duke_Law/>\n\nUnder {{usc|26|163(h)}} of the [[Internal Revenue Code]], the United States allows a home mortgage interest deduction, with several limitations. First, the taxpayer must elect to itemize deductions, and the total itemized deductions must exceed the [[standard deduction]] (otherwise, itemization would not reduce tax). Second, the deduction is limited to interest on debts secured by a principal residence or a second home.  Third, interest is deductible on only the first $1 million of debt used for acquiring, constructing, or substantially improving the residence, ($500,000 if filing separately) or the first $100,000 of home equity debt regardless of the purpose or use of the loan. The cost to the federal government of the mortgage interest deductions in 2018 was approximately $25 billion, down from $60 billion for 2017 as a result of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=Slate_MID >{{ cite news | url=https://slate.com/business/2018/04/its-time-for-the-mortgage-interest-deduction-to-go.html | title=Republicans Gutted the Mortgage Interest Deduction. Democrats Should Finish It Off. | last=Weissmann | first=Jordan | newspaper=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] | date=2018-05-24 | access-date=2019-11-07 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501183155/https://slate.com/business/2018/04/its-time-for-the-mortgage-interest-deduction-to-go.html | archive-date=2018-05-01 | url-status=live | quote=This week, Congress\u2019s Joint Committee on Taxation offered new projections showing just how radical this move was. The report predicts that just 13.8 million households will subtract mortgage interest from their 2018 returns, down from 32.3 million in 2017. The total cost of the deduction will fall from $59.9 billion to $25 billion\u2014a drop of about 58 percent.* }}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, there are additional tax incentives for home ownership.  For example, taxpayers are allowed an exclusion of up to $250,000 ($500,000 for a married couple filing jointly) of capital gains on the sale of real property if the owner used it as primary residence for two of the five years before the date of sale.  Economists have demonstrated that high-cost high-income areas receive most of the tax benefit.  For example, [[San Francisco, California]] receives $26,385 per home while [[El Paso, Texas]] receives $2,153 per home, a 1,225% difference.<ref>See Table 4 in {{cite journal |first=Todd |last=Sinai |first2=Joseph |last2=Gyourko |year=2004 |title=The (Un)changing Geographical Distribution of Housing Tax Benefits: 1980\u20132000 |journal=Tax Policy and the Economy |volume=18 |pages=175\u2013208 |doi=10.1086/tpe.18.20061889 |url=https://repository.upenn.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1057&context=real-estate_papers }}</ref> The five highest income metros receive 87% of tax inflows, with over half going into California alone.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Gyourko |first=Joseph |first2=Todd |last2=Sinai |title=The Spatial Distribution of Housing\u2010Related Ordinary Income Tax Benefits |journal=Real Estate Economics |volume=31 |issue=4 |year=2003 |pages=527\u2013575 |doi=10.1046/j.1080-8620.2003.00076.x |url=https://repository.upenn.edu/real-estate_papers/44 }}</ref>\n\n== Opinions about the deduction ==\n\nThe standard justification for the deduction is that it gives an [[incentive]] for home ownership,<ref name=Lowenstein2006/> but most economists believe the deduction is bad policy and is counterproductive.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Matthews |first1=Dylan |title=America\u2019s biggest housing program is run by the IRS, and it\u2019s a huge giveaway to rich people |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2015/12/11/9901144/mortgage-interest-deduction |website=Vox |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> They note that it increases inequality, is an unnecessary market distortion, and contributes to housing unaffordability.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Casselman |first1=Ben |title=The Tax Deductions Economists Hate |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/the-tax-deductions-economists-hate/ |website=FiveThirtyEight |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[National Association of Realtors]] strongly opposes eliminating the mortgage interest deduction, claiming, \"Housing is the engine that drives the economy, and to even mention reducing the tax benefits of home ownership could endanger property values. Home prices, particularly in high cost areas, could decline 15 percent if recommendations to convert the mortgage interest deduction to a tax credit are implemented.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.realtor.org/government_affairs/mortgage_interest_deduction/index.html |title=NAR: Defending the Mortgage Interest Deduction<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=23 January 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080214232715/http://www.realtor.org/government_affairs/mortgage_interest_deduction/index.html |archive-date=14 February 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Tax Foundation]] argues that few low- and middle-income taxpayers benefit,<ref name=\"whobenefits\">[http://www.taxfoundation.org/news/show/1341.html Who Benefits from the Home Mortgage Interest Deduction?]</ref> calling it [[subsidization]] of the real estate industry.<ref name=\"taxfoundationfacts\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.taxfoundation.org/blog/show/1176.html |title=Some Facts About the Mortgage Interest Deduction |access-date=23 January 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080217212933/http://www.taxfoundation.org/blog/show/1176.html |archive-date=17 February 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Alan Mallach, a senior fellow at the Center for Community Progress and a visiting scholar at the Federal Reserve Bank of Philadelphia, argues that the deduction artificially inflates home prices and is in effect a government subsidy of the real estate industry.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.planmyloan.com/blog/loan-tips-and-tricks/home-loan-how-to-reduce-your-burden/| title=Home Loan: How to Reduce The Burden | publisher=planmyloan.com|accessdate=2014-02-22}}</ref> Critics in the United States also estimate that it contributes between $70 billion and $100 billion annually to the budget deficit.<ref name=\"bdeficit\">[http://www.dailyfinance.com/2011/04/20/eliminate-mortgage-interest-tax-deduction/]</ref>\n\nEconomist [[Edward Glaeser]] remarked in ''The New York Times'' that the policy \"is public paternalism at its worst\" and wrongfully \"encourages people to leave urban areas\" as well as to borrow as much as possible to bet on housing.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://economix.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/15/if-the-tea-party-went-downtown/ | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | first=Edward L. | last=Glaeser | title=If the Tea Party Went Downtown | date=15 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March 2012, [[PBS]] aired an episode of its show [[Need to Know (PBS)|Need to Know]] in which a bipartisan panel discussed tax reform. The panel, which consisted of former Democratic politician [[Eliot Spitzer]], tax law professor Dorothy A. Brown, Reagan domestic policy advisor [[Bruce Bartlett]], and libertarian economist [[Daniel J. Mitchell]], unanimously opposed the federal mortgage interest deduction.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/need-to-know/video/video-cleaning-up-the-tax-mess/13309/ | title= Cleaning up the tax mess | date=9 March 2012 | publisher=PBS }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hidden welfare state]]\n*[[Interest]]\n*[[Land value tax]]\n*[[Loan]]\n*[[Mortgage loan]]\n*[[Qualified residence interest]]\n*[[Tax deduction]]\n*[[Tax policy]]\n*[[Taxable income]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Lowenstein2006>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/05/magazine/305deduction.1.html?pagewanted=2&_r=2 | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | first=Roger | last=Lowenstein | title=Who Needs the Mortgage-Interest Deduction? | date=5 March 2006}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Home Mortgage Interest Deduction}}\n[[Category:Mortgage]]\n[[Category:Income taxes]]\n\n[[nl:Hypotheekrenteaftrek (Nederland)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Taxation}}\nA '''home mortgage interest deduction''' allows taxpayers who [[Owner-occupier|own their homes]] to reduce their [[taxable income]] <ref>http://www.articlesxpert.com/article/1260369/the-multiple-benefits-of-home-loan-tax-exemption/</ref> by the amount of [[interest]] paid on the [[loan]] which is secured by their principal residence (or, sometimes, a [[Vacation property|second home]]).  Most [[Developed country|developed countries]] do not allow a deduction for interest on personal loans, so countries that allow a home mortgage interest deduction have created an exception to those rules. The [[Netherlands]], [[Switzerland]], and the [[United States]] each allow the deduction. In [[Belgium]], [[Denmark]], and [[Ireland]], only a minor part of mortgage interest is deductible.\n\n== Status in countries ==\n\n=== Canada ===\nCanadian federal income tax does not allow a deduction from taxable income for interest on loans secured by the taxpayer's personal residence, but homes used in businesses as a landlord who owns a rental residential property can deduct interest as any other reasonable business expense. The difference being the deduction is allowed only when the property is not used for the taxpayer's personal use but is used as in any other type of business.<ref>https://turbotax.intuit.ca/tax-resources/tax-deductions/is-interest-deductible.jsp</ref> However, there may be additional exclusions for [[passive activity]] losses.\n\nAn indirect method, known as the Smith Manoeuvre, for making interest on mortgage for personal residence tax deductible in Canada is through an asset swap, whereby the homebuyer sells his existing investments, purchases a house in full or in part by the sale, gets a mortgage on the house, and finally, buys back his investments with the money from the mortgage.<ref>https://www.theglobeandmail.com/real-estate/mortgages-and-rates/the-smith-maneuver-a-canadian-mortgage-tax-deductible-plan/article12059456/</ref> The Supreme Court of Canada has ruled in 2001 in the Singleton v. Canada case<ref name=Singleton>{{Cite web |url=http://csc.lexum.umontreal.ca/en/2001/2001scc61/2001scc61.html |title=Supreme Court of Canada: Singleton v. Canada, 2001 2 S.C.R. 1046, 2001 SCC 61 |access-date=29 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100518203119/http://csc.lexum.umontreal.ca/en/2001/2001scc61/2001scc61.html |archive-date=18 May 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> that transactions in the asset swap are to be regarded as distinct, thus rendering the interest on home mortgage acquired as part of the asset swap tax deductible.\n\nThe home ownership rate in Canada was about the same as in the United States in 2008<ref>[http://www.newsweek.com/id/183670 Worthwhile Canadian Initiative]</ref> despite the difference in tax policy.\n\n=== Denmark ===\nIn Denmark part of the interest is deductible. In 1987 it was 73%. In 1993 it was 50% and in 1998 it was 46%. From 1998 to 2001 it was reduced to 32%. It is the plan that in 2019 it will be 25,5%.\n\n=== France ===\nFrance does not allow a home mortgage interest deduction. In 2007, newly elected President [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] proposed creating the deduction as part of his legislative plan for sparking the French economy.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=a9OlqDLbD9sU&refer=home | work=Bloomberg | title=Sarkozy Defeats Royal in French Presidential Runoff (Update5) | date=6 May 2007}}</ref> In August 2007, the [[Constitutional Council of France|Constitutional Council]], the highest court in France, struck down the mortgage interest deduction as unconstitutionally creating a tax advantage that goes far beyond its stated goal of encouraging non-homeowners to buy homes. The Court noted that the deduction would apply to people who already own homes.<ref>http://www.conseil-constitutionnel.fr/decision/2007/2007555/2007555dc.htm (French)</ref>\n\n=== India ===\nHome loan interest portion is deductible (under section 24(b)) up to 150 000 rupees in a tax year for acquiring or constructing a property. The deduction is available only when the construction is complete or you have possession of the property. Interest of pre-construction period is deductible in five equal installments. The first installment is deductible in the year in which construction of property is completed or property acquired. The principal is deductible under section 80C, which has a limit of 150 000 rupees.<ref>''[https://www.easyfinance.com/community/the-multiple-benefits-of-home-loan-tax-exemption/]'', Benefits of Home Loan Tax Exemption</ref><ref>http://mytaxes.in/index.php?topic=9.0 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101127140317/http://mytaxes.in/index.php?topic=9.0 |date=27 November 2010 }} Home Loan Deduction</ref>\n\n=== Netherlands ===\nIn the Netherlands, a part of the interest payments can be deducted for a maximum period of 30 years. The deduction percentage is based on a person's income.<ref>http://www.belastingdienst.nl/variabel/buitenland/en/private_taxpayers/private_taxpayers-12.html  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090401050427/http://www.belastingdienst.nl/variabel/buitenland/en/private_taxpayers/private_taxpayers-12.html |date=1 April 2009 }}</ref> However, before deduction the taxable income is increased by a percentage of the property value (so-called \"notional rental value\"<ref>http://www.belastingdienst.nl/variabel/buitenland/en/private_taxpayers/private_taxpayers-10.html , {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090417022804/http://www.belastingdienst.nl/variabel/buitenland/en/private_taxpayers/private_taxpayers-10.html |date=17 April 2009 }}</ref>) with the reasoning that the property has a potential income-generating purpose.\n\nStill in place currently, the mortgage interest tax deduction is subject to fierce debate, and a political issue during most recent elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nuzakelijk.nl/algemeen/2259623/verkiezingen-2010-hypotheekrenteaftrek-en-huur.html|title=Verkiezingen 2010: hypotheekrenteaftrek en huur|date=1 June 2010|publisher=nuzakelijk.nl|language=Dutch|accessdate=23 February 2012}}</ref> Although largely an emotional point of discussion with the Dutch electorate, and described by many as \"political suicide\", most Dutch people believe that the mortgage interest tax deduction will eventually be reformed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vorige.nrc.nl/krant/article1739149.ece/Taboe_voor_politici,_niet_voor_de_kiezers_|title=Taboe voor politici, niet voor de kiezers|date=11 April 2006|publisher=NRC Handelsblad|language=Dutch|accessdate=23 February 2012}}</ref> Many reasons for abolishment have been identified, often fuelled by a political ideology (e.g. creating house price inflation, limiting government earnings in times of economic downturn, mortgage interest tax deduction is increasing already high tax levels in the Netherlands, benefiting high income individuals more disproportionally).<ref>[[:nl:Hypotheekrenteaftrek]]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nos.nl/artikel/65097-hypotheekrente-weer-ter-discussie.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120929100106/http://nos.nl/artikel/65097-hypotheekrente-weer-ter-discussie.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-09-29 |title=Hypotheekrente weer ter discussie |date=2007-10-17 |publisher=NOS Nieuws |language=Dutch |accessdate=23 February 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bouwendnederland.nl/SiteCollectionDocuments/Argumenten%20voor%20-%20tegen%20beperking%20hypotheekrenteafttrek.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724145621/http://www.bouwendnederland.nl/SiteCollectionDocuments/Argumenten%20voor%20-%20tegen%20beperking%20hypotheekrenteafttrek.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 July 2011 |title=Argumenten voor - tegen beperking hypotheekrenteaftrek |publisher=BouwendNederland |language=Dutch |accessdate=23 February 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hypotheker.nl/Hypotheken/Hypotheekrenteaftrek/Veelgestelde+vragen/|title=Hypotheekrenteaftrek: Veelgestelde vragen|publisher=De hypotheker|language=Dutch|accessdate=23 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nAs it stands now, Dutch politicians and other organisations research possible strategies to end interest payments tax deduction and are fuelling public debate to prepare the Dutch public for eventual abolishment.<ref name=\"tns-nipo.com\">http://www.tns-nipo.com/pages/nieuws-pers-vnipo.asp?file=persvannipo\\pol_woningmarkt-08062010.htm {{Failed verification|date=February 2012}}</ref> Only 18% of the Dutch public support eliminating the mortgage interest deduction entirely.<ref name=\"tns-nipo.com\"/>\n\n=== Norway ===\nNorway considers ''any'' interest paid, whether it is for a home mortgage or other debt, as a deductible expense.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://snl.no/rentefradrag|title=rentefradrag|publisher=Store norske leksikon|language=Norwegian|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref> The result is a reduction of the tax bill of 25% of all interest paid.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nettavisen.no/na24/smartepenger/rentefradraget-blir-mindre-verdt/3423145132.html|title=Rentefradraget blir mindre verdt|publisher=Nettavisen|language=Norwegian|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref> The fact that the government in effect subsidises 25% of the interest bill has made home ownership highly beneficial in Norway, and critics argue that the deduction has increased the cost of real estate. The [[Center Party (Norway)|Center Party]] has proposed reducing the deduction.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aftenbladet.no/nyheter/politikk/Sp-vil-kutte-rentefradrag-pa-private-boliglan-3153597.html#.UajYFkBJSZg|title=Sp vil kutte rentefradrag p\u00e5 private boligl\u00e5n|last=Natland|first=Jarle|date=7 April 2013|publisher=Aftenbladet|language=Norwegian|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Sweden ===\nA tax credit of 30% of interest up until 100,000 SEK, and 21% over that amount.<ref>https://www.skatteverket.se/privat/skatter/arbeteinkomst/avdragslexikon/r.4.5fc8c94513259a4ba1d800042806.html</ref> The amount was about 10,000 SEK per taxpaying person with debts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.svd.se/naringsliv/pengar/bostad/slopat-ranteavdrag-hot-for-familjer_3963920.svd|title=Slopat r\u00e4nteavdrag hot f\u00f6r familjer|date=29 September 2014|publisher=Svenska dagbladet|language=Swedish|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== United Kingdom ===\n\nThe United Kingdom introduced a scheme called [[Mortgage interest relief at source|MIRAS]] in 1983 to allow mortgage interest to be tax deductible. It was abolished in 2000.\n\n=== United States ===\n\nPrior to the [[Tax Reform Act of 1986]] (TRA86), the interest on all personal loans (including credit card debt) was deductible. TRA86 eliminated that broad deduction, but left the narrower home mortgage interest deduction.<ref name=Lowenstein2006 /><ref name=Duke_Law>{{ cite web | url=https://scholarship.law.duke.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1561&context=lcp | title=THE ACCIDENTAL DEDUCTION: A HISTORY AND CRITIQUE OF THE TAX SUBSIDY FOR MORTGAGE INTEREST | last=VENTRY | first=DENNIS | publisher=Duke University Law | date=2009 | accessdate=2018-01-19 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120126190952/https://scholarship.law.duke.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1561&context=lcp | archive-date=2012-01-26 | url-status=live | pages=236 | quote=<blockquote>Whatever the original motivation for the consumer interest deduction, one thing is clear: Congress did not see it as a way of promoting homeownership. ... Part II of this article examines the origins of the deduction for personal interest alongside the birth of the modern federal income tax and concludes that the deduction had nothing to do with encouraging or rewarding homeownership.</blockquote> }}</ref> While some Americans may believe that Congress created the home mortgage interest deduction as a way to encourage home ownership,<ref name=NYT_MID2>{{ cite web | url=https://economix.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/08/06/the-sacrosanct-mortgage-interest-deduction/ | title=The Sacrosanct Mortgage Interest Deduction | last=Bartlett | first=Bruce | publisher=The New York Times Company | date=2013-08-06 | accessdate=2018-01-19 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020203627/https://economix.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/08/06/the-sacrosanct-mortgage-interest-deduction/ | archive-date=2017-10-20 | url-status=live | quote=Contrary to popular belief, the mortgage interest deduction wasn\u2019t adopted to encourage home ownership. }}</ref><ref name=Tax_Policy_1>{{ cite web | url=http://www.taxpolicycenter.org/sites/default/files/briefing-book/4.8.2-do_existing_tax_incentives_increase_homeownership.pdf | title=Do existing tax incentives increase homeownership? | publisher=Taxpolicycenter.org | accessdate=2018-01-19 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119214832/http://www.taxpolicycenter.org/sites/default/files/briefing-book/4.8.2-do_existing_tax_incentives_increase_homeownership.pdf | archive-date=2018-01-19 | url-status=live | quote=Contrary to popular belief, the mortgage interest deduction was not added to the tax code to encourage home ownership. The deduction existed at the birth of the income tax in 1913\u2014a tax explicitly designed to hit only the richest individuals, a group for whom homeownership rates were not a social concern. }}</ref> historians point out that this was never the case, as explained in a New York Times article that notes that, in 1913, when interest deductions started, Congress \"certainly wasn't thinking of the interest deduction as a stepping-stone to middle-class home ownership, because the tax excluded the first $3,000 (or for married couples, $4,000) of income; less than 1 percent of the population earned more than that;\" moreover, during that era, most people who purchased homes paid upfront rather than taking out a mortgage. Rather, the reason for the deduction was that in a nation of small proprietors, it was more difficult to separate business and personal expenses, and so it was simpler to just allow deduction of all interest.<ref name=Lowenstein2006/><ref name=Duke_Law/>\n\nUnder {{usc|26|163(h)}} of the [[Internal Revenue Code]], the United States allows a home mortgage interest deduction, with several limitations. First, the taxpayer must elect to itemize deductions, and the total itemized deductions must exceed the [[standard deduction]] (otherwise, itemization would not reduce tax). Second, the deduction is limited to interest on debts secured by a principal residence or a second home.  Third, interest is deductible on only the first $1 million of debt used for acquiring, constructing, or substantially improving the residence, ($500,000 if filing separately) or the first $100,000 of home equity debt regardless of the purpose or use of the loan. The cost to the federal government of the mortgage interest deductions in 2018 was approximately $25 billion, down from $60 billion for 2017 as a result of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=Slate_MID >{{ cite news | url=https://slate.com/business/2018/04/its-time-for-the-mortgage-interest-deduction-to-go.html | title=Republicans Gutted the Mortgage Interest Deduction. Democrats Should Finish It Off. | last=Weissmann | first=Jordan | newspaper=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] | date=2018-05-24 | access-date=2019-11-07 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501183155/https://slate.com/business/2018/04/its-time-for-the-mortgage-interest-deduction-to-go.html | archive-date=2018-05-01 | url-status=live | quote=This week, Congress\u2019s Joint Committee on Taxation offered new projections showing just how radical this move was. The report predicts that just 13.8 million households will subtract mortgage interest from their 2018 returns, down from 32.3 million in 2017. The total cost of the deduction will fall from $59.9 billion to $25 billion\u2014a drop of about 58 percent.* }}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, there are additional tax incentives for home ownership.  For example, taxpayers are allowed an exclusion of up to $250,000 ($500,000 for a married couple filing jointly) of capital gains on the sale of real property if the owner used it as primary residence for two of the five years before the date of sale.  Economists have demonstrated that high-cost high-income areas receive most of the tax benefit.  For example, [[San Francisco, California]] receives $26,385 per home while [[El Paso, Texas]] receives $2,153 per home, a 1,225% difference.<ref>See Table 4 in {{cite journal |first=Todd |last=Sinai |first2=Joseph |last2=Gyourko |year=2004 |title=The (Un)changing Geographical Distribution of Housing Tax Benefits: 1980\u20132000 |journal=Tax Policy and the Economy |volume=18 |pages=175\u2013208 |doi=10.1086/tpe.18.20061889 |url=https://repository.upenn.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1057&context=real-estate_papers }}</ref> The five highest income metros receive 87% of tax inflows, with over half going into California alone.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Gyourko |first=Joseph |first2=Todd |last2=Sinai |title=The Spatial Distribution of Housing\u2010Related Ordinary Income Tax Benefits |journal=Real Estate Economics |volume=31 |issue=4 |year=2003 |pages=527\u2013575 |doi=10.1046/j.1080-8620.2003.00076.x |url=https://repository.upenn.edu/real-estate_papers/44 }}</ref>\n\n== Opinions about the deduction ==\n\nThe standard justification for the deduction is that it gives an [[incentive]] for home ownership,<ref name=Lowenstein2006/> but most economists believe the deduction is bad policy and is counterproductive.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Matthews |first1=Dylan |title=America\u2019s biggest housing program is run by the IRS, and it\u2019s a huge giveaway to rich people |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2015/12/11/9901144/mortgage-interest-deduction |website=Vox |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> They note that it increases inequality, is an unnecessary market distortion, and contributes to housing unaffordability.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Casselman |first1=Ben |title=The Tax Deductions Economists Hate |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/the-tax-deductions-economists-hate/ |website=FiveThirtyEight |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[National Association of Realtors]] strongly opposes eliminating the mortgage interest deduction, claiming, \"Housing is the engine that drives the economy, and to even mention reducing the tax benefits of home ownership could endanger property values. Home prices, particularly in high cost areas, could decline 15 percent if recommendations to convert the mortgage interest deduction to a tax credit are implemented.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.realtor.org/government_affairs/mortgage_interest_deduction/index.html |title=NAR: Defending the Mortgage Interest Deduction<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=23 January 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080214232715/http://www.realtor.org/government_affairs/mortgage_interest_deduction/index.html |archive-date=14 February 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Tax Foundation]] argues that few low- and middle-income taxpayers benefit,<ref name=\"whobenefits\">[http://www.taxfoundation.org/news/show/1341.html Who Benefits from the Home Mortgage Interest Deduction?]</ref> calling it [[subsidization]] of the real estate industry.<ref name=\"taxfoundationfacts\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.taxfoundation.org/blog/show/1176.html |title=Some Facts About the Mortgage Interest Deduction |access-date=23 January 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080217212933/http://www.taxfoundation.org/blog/show/1176.html |archive-date=17 February 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Alan Mallach, a senior fellow at the Center for Community Progress and a visiting scholar at the Federal Reserve Bank of Philadelphia, argues that the deduction artificially inflates home prices and is in effect a government subsidy of the real estate industry.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.planmyloan.com/blog/loan-tips-and-tricks/home-loan-how-to-reduce-your-burden/| title=Home Loan: How to Reduce The Burden | publisher=planmyloan.com|accessdate=2014-02-22}}</ref> Critics in the United States also estimate that it contributes between $70 billion and $100 billion annually to the budget deficit.<ref name=\"bdeficit\">[http://www.dailyfinance.com/2011/04/20/eliminate-mortgage-interest-tax-deduction/]</ref>\n\nEconomist [[Edward L. Glaeser]] remarked in ''The New York Times'' that the policy \"is public paternalism at its worst\" and wrongfully \"encourages people to leave urban areas\" as well as to borrow as much as possible to bet on housing.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://economix.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/03/15/if-the-tea-party-went-downtown/ | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | first=Edward L. | last=Glaeser | title=If the Tea Party Went Downtown | date=15 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March 2012, [[PBS]] aired an episode of its show [[Need to Know (PBS)|Need to Know]] in which a bipartisan panel discussed tax reform. The panel, which consisted of former Democratic politician [[Eliot Spitzer]], tax law professor Dorothy A. Brown, Reagan domestic policy advisor [[Bruce Bartlett]], and libertarian economist [[Daniel J. Mitchell]], unanimously opposed the federal mortgage interest deduction.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/need-to-know/video/video-cleaning-up-the-tax-mess/13309/ | title= Cleaning up the tax mess | date=9 March 2012 | publisher=PBS }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hidden welfare state]]\n*[[Interest]]\n*[[Land value tax]]\n*[[Loan]]\n*[[Mortgage loan]]\n*[[Qualified residence interest]]\n*[[Tax deduction]]\n*[[Tax policy]]\n*[[Taxable income]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Lowenstein2006>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/05/magazine/305deduction.1.html?pagewanted=2&_r=2 | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | first=Roger | last=Lowenstein | title=Who Needs the Mortgage-Interest Deduction? | date=5 March 2006}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Home Mortgage Interest Deduction}}\n[[Category:Mortgage]]\n[[Category:Income taxes]]\n\n[[nl:Hypotheekrenteaftrek (Nederland)]]\n", "name_user": "RedHotPear", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Home_mortgage_interest_deduction"}
